# Zombie Blaster — Game Architecture

## Overview
Zombie Blaster is a browser-based multiplayer zombie platformer RPG (MapleStory-inspired).
- Frontend: Angular (UI/menus) + Canvas/WebGL (game rendering)
- Backend: Node.js (game server, authoritative state, multiplayer)
- Multiplayer: up to 4 players per session via WebSockets

## Character System
- 5-6 character classes, each with unique stats, skills, and progression.
- Stats system inspired by MapleStory: STR, DEX, INT, LUK (or similar) affecting damage, speed, crit, etc.
- Leveling through grinding zombies; XP curve scales with level.
- Each class has a skill tree or skill list that unlocks/upgrades with levels.

## Server Authority
- The server is the source of truth for all game state: positions, HP, damage, drops, XP.
- Client sends inputs (movement, attack commands); server validates and broadcasts results.
- Never trust client-computed damage, loot, or position — always verify server-side.

## Separation of Concerns
- **Angular components**: menus, HUD, inventory, character select, lobby, chat UI.
- **Game engine / Canvas**: platformer rendering, sprite animation, physics, particle effects.
- **Node.js server**: game loop, collision detection (authoritative), combat resolution, session management.
- **Shared types**: interfaces for messages, character stats, items — shared between client and server.

## Naming Conventions
- Game entities: `Zombie`, `Player`, `Item`, `Skill`, `Map`, `Room`.
- Services: `GameStateService`, `CombatService`, `LobbyService`, `CharacterService`.
- Events/messages: `PlayerJoined`, `ZombieSpawned`, `DamageDealt`, `LootDropped`.

## Performance
- Game loop runs at a fixed tick rate on the server (e.g., 20-60 ticks/sec).
- Client interpolates between server updates for smooth rendering.
- Minimize payload size for WebSocket messages (use compact formats).
